\description{
The function is designed for field situations where the physical grid is fixed
before design construction, planting or harvesting follows a continuous
field-book order rather than rectangular replicate boundaries, and repeated
checks in every incomplete block are required. Replicate boundaries are
determined by position in the traversal stream, not by geometric subdivision
of the grid. This means replicate 2 begins exactly where replicate 1 ends in
stream order, and all surplus cells accumulate at the tail of the stream as
unused positions.

Given those constraints, the function proceeds as follows:
\enumerate{
\item Generates the global field stream from \code{n_rows}, \code{n_cols}, \code{order},
and \code{serpentine}.
\item Determines the number of incomplete blocks supportable per replicate
given entry count, check count, and \code{min_entry_slots_per_block}.
\item Partitions each replicate segment into incomplete blocks.
\item Assigns checks and entries to blocks subject to the capacity plan.
\item Improves entry arrangement heuristically to reduce local concentration
of genetically or structurally similar material.
\item Places surplus cells as trailing \code{NA} at the end of the stream.
\item Optionally refines placement via dispersion optimization.
\item Optionally evaluates the resulting design under a mixed-model framework.
}
}
\details{
\code{alpha_rc_stream()} builds a row-column field design over a fixed \verb{n_rows x n_cols}
grid. The full grid is traversed in a single ordered stream, partitioned into
contiguous replicate segments, and each segment is further subdivided into
incomplete blocks of possibly unequal size. Within every replicate, each entry
appears exactly once. Within every incomplete block, every check appears exactly
once. Field cells that cannot be assigned to any replicate are left as trailing
\code{NA} positions at the end of the stream.
}
\section{Stream-based versus rectangle-based layout}{

The distinction from conventional row-column design functions is that
replicates are defined by stream position, not by rectangular spatial
partitions. This matters when operational field movement is continuous
(row-wise or column-wise), when replicate boundaries are logistical rather
than geometric, and when all unused cells should fall at the end of the
sequence rather than within replicate areas. The incomplete block structure
is consequently a function of stream segment length and capacity constraints,
not of field shape.
}

\section{Plot count identity}{

Let \code{E} be the number of entries, \code{C} the number of checks, \code{R} the number
of replicates, and \code{b} the number of incomplete blocks per replicate. The
number of used plots per replicate is:

\deqn{E + b \times C}

and the total number of used plots across the trial is:

\deqn{R \times (E + b \times C)}

This total must not exceed the fixed field capacity \verb{n_rows x n_cols}. The
function chooses \code{b} to be as large as possible subject to
\code{min_entry_slots_per_block}, \code{max_blocks_per_rep} if supplied, and the
capacity constraint. Efficiency evaluation and dispersion optimization
operate only on non-\code{NA} plots.
}

\section{Argument dependencies}{


\strong{Grouping source}

When \code{cluster_source = "Family"}, grouping comes directly from
\code{check_families} and \code{entry_families}; \code{GRM}, \code{A}, \code{id_map},
\code{cluster_method}, \code{cluster_seed}, \code{cluster_attempts}, and \code{n_pcs_use} are
all ignored. When \code{cluster_source = "GRM"}, \code{GRM} is required and \code{id_map}
is needed only if entry names differ from \code{rownames(GRM)}; grouping is
derived by PCA followed by clustering. The same applies for
\code{cluster_source = "A"} with matrix \code{A}.

\strong{Efficiency evaluation}

When \code{eval_efficiency = FALSE}, all efficiency arguments are ignored.
When \code{eval_efficiency = TRUE} and \code{treatment_effect = "fixed"}, fixed-treatment
contrast precision is computed and \code{prediction_type}, \code{K}, and \code{line_id_map}
are ignored. When \code{treatment_effect = "random"}, \code{prediction_type} becomes
active. \code{"none"} skips random-effect efficiency; \code{"IID"} treats entry effects
as independent and ignores \code{K} and \code{line_id_map}; \code{"GBLUP"} and \code{"PBLUP"}
require \code{K}, with \code{line_id_map} needed if treatment IDs differ from
\code{rownames(K)}.

\strong{Residual structure}

When \code{residual_structure = "IID"}, \code{rho_row} and \code{rho_col} are ignored.
\code{"AR1"} uses only \code{rho_row}. \code{"AR1xAR1"} uses both \code{rho_row} and \code{rho_col}.
All residual structure arguments are inactive when \code{eval_efficiency = FALSE}.

\strong{Dispersion optimization}

When \code{use_dispersion = FALSE}, all dispersion arguments are ignored.
When \code{use_dispersion = TRUE}, \code{dispersion_source} selects the relationship
matrix used for pairwise similarity scoring: \code{"K"} requires \code{K} (with
optional \code{line_id_map}), \code{"A"} requires \code{A}, \code{"GRM"} requires \code{GRM}.

\strong{Interface-continuity arguments}

\code{warn_and_correct}, \code{fix_rows}, \code{spatial_engine}, \code{dense_max_n}, and
\code{check_position_pattern} are retained for interface consistency with related
functions. They do not alter the stream-based design logic.
}

